    <h1>4&#xD;&#xA;NON-FIC&#xAD;TION/PO&#xAD;ETRY ROBERT YEO AT EIGHTY: A CEL&#xAD;E&#xAD;BRA&#xAD;TION</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE BOOKS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Edited by Is­mail S. Talib</p>
    <p>Epi­gram Books/Pa­per­back/</p>
    <p>224 pages/$20.22/Ma­jor book­stores</p>
    <p>This vol­ume pays tribute to Yeo, the vet­eran poet, nov­el­ist and play­wright who turned 80 ear­lier this year. Yeo wrote lo­cal clas­sics such as the 1974 play,</p>
    <p>Are You There, Sin­ga­pore?, and 1986 novel The Ad­ven­tures Of Holden Heng. He has re­ceived ac­co­lades like the South-east Asia Write Award.</p>
    <p>Col­lected in th­ese pages are not only crit­i­cal es­says on Yeo’s work, but also po­ems in­spired by him, penned by the likes of Gwee Li Sui, Cyril Wong and Leong Liew Geok, and well wishes from Sin­ga­pore’s literati.</p>

